scientific information on their anatomy, history, distribution, position in the water, and environmental status. Foremost jellyfish expert Lisa-ann Gershwin provides an insightful look at the natural history and biology of each of these spellbinding creatures, while offering a timely take on their place in the rapidly changing and deteriorating condition of the oceans. Readers will learn about immortal jellyfish who live and die and live again as well as those who camouflage themselves amid sea grasses and shells, hiding in plain sight. Approachably written and based in the latest science and ecology, this colorful book provides an authoritative guide to these ethereal marine wonders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aJellyfishes. 0aNatural history. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh  ajellyfish, ocean, marine life, blooms, evolution, predator, climate change, habitat, global warming, nature, environment, conservation, preservation, rising temperatures, toxicity, black sea nettles, endangered, biology, zoology, science, anatomy, distribution, natural history, immortality, aging, camouflage, ecology, nonfiction, bioluminescence, drifting, photography, physiology, oceanography.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226287706423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226287706/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles